deck_excerpt: PUNK finally received it's two incredible support cards in Masterduel!
deck_description:
The Masterduel selection pack "Wrath of the Tyrants" has unleashed incredible PUNK support that powers up the strategy to another level of power and consistency! Rising Scale functions as an incredible extender summoning itself and another PUNK from deck, allowing these Cyberpunks to power through interruptions and handtraps. JAM FEVER! grants PUNK a unique monster negate as well, raising the power level of their endboards and insulating plays through handtraps like Nibiru. 
 
Lacrima the Crimson Tears along with Agnumday also released with Wrath of the Tyrants, meaning Fiendsmith is now completely available to any strategy that can run it! Fiendsmith allows PUNK to play through handtraps especially Droll, since Fiendsmith cards summon from deck or send to the GY rather than adding them to the hand.  If your PUNK deck was stopped by too much interruption, you can pivot to the Fiendsmith engine instead with any two bodies thanks to Moon of the Closed Heaven! 
 
Combining the excellent new PUNK support with nearly full power Fiendsmith the PUNK duelist can end on a multilayered board with 8+ interruptions in the field, hand, GY and backrow! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
In contrast to other iterations of this PUNK, I prefer a sizeable PUNK deck consisting of 60 cards. It is 60 cards since one Ze Amin is full PUNK combo thanks to Rising Scale, and there are 16 copies of Ze Amin (3 Ze Amin, 3 Ogre, 3 Foxy Tune, 3 Rising Scale, 3 Emergency Teleport and 1 Small World) giving the duelist a fair chance of drawing into it with their starting hand despite the 60 cards. 60 cards also make it less likely that you will hard draw your garnets (Sharakusai, Deer Note, Wa Gon, Jam Session, Lurrie, In Paradise, Lacrima, Birth) that are essential for the combos in your PUNK, Fiendsmith and Kashtira engines. 
 
The two archetypes in this deck are of course PUNK (21 cards), Fiendsmith (8 cards) and Kashtira (5 cards). PUNK cards are your starters for the main combo while Fiendsmith/Kashtira are extenders that bait interruption and can break through boards. 
 
The usual "Maxx C" package is included with 1 Crossout, 2 Called By the Grave, 3 Ash Blossom and 3 Maxx C. The Gamma package also is there to counter Maxx C and any other handtraps with 1 Gamma and 1 Driver. The rest of the handtrap staples are included as Small World bridges to search your starters. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of PUNK remains the same - interrupt your opponent as much as possible while building as much resource advantage as you can with multiple draws and searches through your multiple engines. The turn after, if your opponent hasn't surrendered yet, both PUNK and Fiendsmith have massive follow-up to enable an easy OTK. If your Fiendsmith cards are still in the GY and Field, they can recur and resummon themselves to generate a lot of attack while simultaneously picking apart your opponent's board! The PUNK cards have follow-up to, since Jam Session and Amazing Dragon is on the field and Dragon Drive is in the GY. Both engines can OTK independently!
 
The combo for this strategy is the standard PUNK combo -> Fiendsmith combo via the two spare bodies on the field. This is possible using a singular Ze Amin!
 
PUNK Ze Amin = Draw 2 cards (several handtraps in hand) + JAM FEVER! (monster negate destroy) + PUNK Trap (1 pop/negate) + Desirae (omninegate) or High Wave King Caesar/Paradise (double summon negate and targeted send) + 
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo using new support) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Rising Scale.
  2. Link summon Almiraj using Ze Amin.
  3. Summon Rising Scale from hand using Ze Amin in the GY. 
  4. Activate Rising Scale's on-summon effect to summon Sharakusai from deck.
  5. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Rising Scale. 
  6. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  7. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  8. Activate Jam Session. 
  9. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  10. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Madame Spider from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Sharakusai from GY. 
  11. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  12. XYZ summon JAM FEVER! by overlaying on top of Dragon Drive.
  13. Special summon Madam Spider from hand using Jam Session. Madame Spider searches for PUNK trap (I prefer Nashiwari Surprise targeted pop for this current meta) from deck. 
  14. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card a second time. 
  15. (The following is the Fiendsmith combo) 
  16. Link summon Moon of the Closed Heaven using Madam Spider + Sharakusai.
  17. Moon of the Closed Heaven is FULL FIENDSMITH COMBO! You don't need me to detail you on this part, you've probably seen and done this plenty of times before. You can either end on High Wave King Caesar's double summon negate + Crimson Tear's mill of Paradise OR you can summon Desirae for an on-field omni-negate. 
From 1 Ze Amin, you get up to 5 interruptions and a draw 2 (potentially handtraps)! Of course, this is the simplest endboard. Endboards get better and stronger the more extenders you have. It's possible on the biggest boards to end on 10+ interruptions with 3 draws if you're allowed to combo uninterrupted. You'll generally have 5+ cards in hand if you're allowed to full combo since you draw 2-3 cards, so you'll have plenty of handtraps and follow-up.
 
If you're interrupted mid-combo by a turn-ending card, your plan B is to pivot into the Fiendsmith combo or sit on Psychic End Punisher.
 
Going second, hopefully your 20 handtraps simplify the gamestate enough to the point your in-engine combo, supplemental engines and extenders are enough to allow you to play the game through your opponent's interruption. 
 
Remember that 1 single uninterrupted Ze Amin + discard is an OTK!
 
1 Ze Amin + 1 discard can make Amazing Dragon synchro summoned with Rising Carp + Ze Amin clears 2-4 cards from the board while enabling it to attack twice with 3600ATK accompanied with Dragon Drive (2700ATK) totalling 9900 ATK! 
 
PUNK Ze Amin + 1 discard = 3600ATK Amazing Dragon that can attack twice, bounce 4 cards your opponent controls with Amazing Dragon, 2700 ATK Dragon Drive.
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Foxy Tune effect to discard 1 card in hand to summon Sharakusai from deck. 
  3. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Ze Amin. 
  4. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  6. Activate Jam Session. 
  7. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  8. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Ze Amin from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Rising Carp from GY. 
  9. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  10. Special summon Ze Amin from hand using Jam Session.
  11. Synchro Summon Amazing Dragon using Ze Amin + Rising Carp.
  12. CL1 Amazing Dragon to bounce up to 4 cards your opponent controls, CL2 Rising Carp targeting Amazing Dragon enabling it to attack twice, CL3 Ze Amin targeting Amazing Dragon boosting it's ATK by 600.
GENERAL TIPS
  • If you get hit by Droll & Lockbird, Dimension Shifter, or even Maxx "C," your typical plan B is to pivot into Fiendsmith combo or synchro summon Psychic End Punisher. 
  • If you suspect your opponent has handtraps like Ash or Veiler, bait out you opponent's by playing your Fiendsmith and Kashtira cards first. Afterwards you can full combo with PUNK! 
  • Other good supplemental engines that synergize with PUNK are Horus, Millenium, Bystial and Gold Pride! Feel free to replace Kashtira/Fiendsmith with these strategies. 
  • With Necroquip Princess' effect, you can draw an additional card when you activate Ogre Dance or Foxy Tune's search. In that scenario, you play your Fiendsmith cards first.
  • If you successfully resolve Psy-Frame handtrap during your turn, you can synchro it with Driver to summon Dragon Drive and search for your PUNK starters. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I have been playing PUNK since it came out in Grand Creators back at 2023, and it's one of the most fun decks I've ever had the pleasure of piloting! It's 2025, and it's incredible these cyberpunk performers get amazingly powerful support! PUNK can now comfortably catch up to the big meta decks plaguing Masterduel ladder like White Forest, Yubel, Snake-Eyes and Blue-Eyes quite easily thanks to Rising Scale, JAM FEVER! and full power Fiendsmith. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

Get ready to see an incredible celestial display! This isn't your typical Agent deck – we've brought in the K9 Interceptors, advanced robotic guardians from the future, to protect the sacred Sanctuary in the Sky. Observe as the brilliant Mystical Shine Balls transform into powerful Hyperions, supported by the disruptive force of Nibiru and the banishing strength of the Bystials.

But there's more! Our dedicated K9 units aren't just for show. They're equipped with "Cases" and "Liberation" technology, changing the course of duels with surprising forced returns and clever extra deck summons. Need to stop your opponent's strategies? Ash Blossom and Infinite Impermanence are ready. Want explosive power? Lightning Storm and Pot of Desires will energize your divine engine.

And the Extra Deck? It's a collection of formidable threats for your opponent. From the devastating Bystial Dis Pater to the cosmic disruption of Chaos Angel and the relentless attacks of the K9 "Werewolf" and "Ripper," every summon is a precise move.

This deck combines the ethereal elegance of the Agents with the advanced ferocity of the K9 units, creating a unique and unpredictable playstyle that will leave your opponents defeated. Enter the Sanctuary, unleash the guardians, and experience a new level of divine power!

Typus Romae antiquae! Reliquarium dives

 

Contemplationis excelsae Tempori relictae

 

Per saecula sepulta pompae et potentiae!

 

Tandem—tandem—post tot dies

 

Peregrinationis fessae et sitis ardentis,

 

(Sitis fontium doctrinae quae in te iacent,)

 

Genulo procumbo, vir mutatus et humilis,

 

Inter umbras tuas, et sic intus bibo

 

Ipsa anima mea magnitudinem tuam, caliginem et gloriam!

 

Vastitas! et Aetas! et Memorias Veterum!

 

Silentium! et Desolatio! et Nox obscura!

 

Te nunc sentio—te in viribus tuis sentio—

 

O incantationes certiores quam umquam rex Iudaeus

 

Doctae in hortis Gethsemani!

 

O incantationes potentiores quam rapta Chaldaea

 

Semper de stellis quietis deductae!

 

Hic, ubi heros cecidit, columna cadit!

 

Hic, ubi aquila imitatrix auro fulgebat,

 

Vigilia nocturna vespertilionem fuscum tenet!

 

Hic, ubi dominae Romanae crines aurei

 

Ad ventum agitabant, nunc arundinem et carduum agitant!

 

Hic, ubi in solio aureo rex incumbebat,

 

Labitur, velut spectrum, ad domum suam marmoream,

 

Illuminata luce pallida—luce pallida lunae cornutae,

 

Lacerta lapidum celeris et silens!

 

Sed manete! hi muri—hae porticus hedera tectae—

 

Hae bases putrescentes—hae tristes et nigrae virgae—

 

Hae vagae entablementa—haec frangens zophora—

 

Hae cornices fractae—haec naufragium—haec ruina—

 

Hi lapides—heu! hi lapides grisei—suntne omnes—

 

Omnes famosi, et colossalia relicta

 

A Horis corrosis Fato et mihi?

 

“Non omnes”—respondent mihi Echoes—“non omnes!”

 

“Soni prophetici et clamosi, oriuntur in aeternum

 

“A nobis, et ab omni Ruina, ad sapientes,

 

“Tanquam melodia a Memnone ad Solem.

 

“Nos regimus corda virorum potentissimorum—regimus

 

“*** imperio despotico omnes mentes gigantes.

 

“Non sumus impotentes—nos lapides pallidi.

 

“Non omnis nostra potentia abest—non omnis nostra fama—

 

“Non omnis magia nostrae altae famae—

 

“Non omne miraculum quod nos circumdat—

 

“Non omnia mysteria quae in nobis iacent—

 

“Non omnes memoriae quae pendent

 

“Et circum nos haerent velut vestimentum,

 

“Nos induens veste plus quam gloriae.”

deck_description: from the YouTuber @thecallieffect

Fur Hire is one of my favorite decks, P.u.n.k is my favorite engine so ... I tried to make it good enough for Ranking. Not a deck to climb up fast and counter anything, but damn fun, and better than what I expected. (Please don't waste UR thinking you're going to Master with it)

 

I don’t really like using Runnick Spright as an engine for Fur Hire, so I tried building something with what I already had in my collection. It’s not optimized, focused on making some Link summon without any trouble and some good synchro, drawing 6 cards with Folgo, and it’s been working surprisingly well in Diamond ranks. (And by "surprisingly," I mean having a couple of negates on board plus Apollousa tends to work in pretty much any deck… )

 

Have fun!

Sky Striker is getting insane support. Will it be top tier again? Likely not, but it's getting the tools it needs to survive. Zero gives Striker a definitive boss monster that is a viable option going first and second. Without the restriction of Zero needing to be Link Summoned, you can gain more traction turn one with Linkage.

 

Going First Combo Example 1: Engage + Linkage

Engage add Raye. Link into Kagari and add back Engage. Engage add Multirole. In End Phase, Shizuku add Widow Anchor and use it. Use Linkage to summon Zero. Zero add a card from deck to hand. Multirole set back Widow Anchor.

 

Going First Combo Example 2: Raye/Roze/Hornet Drones + Engage

Engage add Linkage. Summon Raye/Roze or Activate Hornet Drones, link into Kagari to add back Engage. Engage add Multirole. Link into Shizuku. In End Phase, Shizuku add Widow Anchor and use it. Linkage send Shizuku to summon Zero. Zero add a card from deck to hand. Multirole set back Widow Anchor.

deck_excerpt: That was an army. Now it's a Graveyard.
deck_description:
Cute Play. Here's why it doesn't matter. 
Evilswarm Exciton Knight and boardbreakers combine to erase your opponents' boards—and their recovery.

Deckmaster: Magical Musketeer Starfire 
Domain Restriction: LIGHT // FIEND
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Catagories:

This strategy builds upon 3 simple strategies:

  • Neutralize
  • Remove
  • Eliminate

This strategy is why the deck has 90% boardbreakers.

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Magical Musketeer Starfire 
- Summon out a lv4 from deck to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight 
- LIGHT//FIEND to make Fiendsmith's Requiem and/or Magical Musketeer Max 

Magical Musketeer Starfire is a powerful Magical Musketeer monster that can be summon out Magical Musketeer Calamity if we activate a boardbreaker in the same column as she is in. After using her effect, you can make Magical Musketeer Max in order to accue more resources, and resummon her from GY using Magical Musketeer Calamity.  This boost of resources is useful to have more boardbreakers while still maintaining the 2 LIGHT//FIEND necessiary to create a Evilswarm Exciton Knight and wipe the board. 

Magical Musketeer Max adds: 

  • Magical Musket - Cross-********** 
  • Magical Musket - Desperado 
  • Magical Musket - Last Stand 

Magical Musketeer Starfire summons:

  • Magical Musketeer Calamity 
  • Magical Musketeer Caspar 
  • Magical Musketeer Doc 
  • Magical Musketeer Wild 

The additional influx of LIGHT//FIEND into our GY allows us to more freely use Fiendsmith's Sequence to fusion summon Fiendsmith's Desirae with. The most ideal situation will be using Fiendsmith's Sequence to summon Fiendsmith's Desirae while still maintaining an Fiendsmith Engraver and Lacrima the Crimson Tears in the GY.
Combo:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-71140535 

What is this deck's combos?
- Use Fiendsmith engine recursivly!
- Use Magical Musketeer Starfire to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight! 
- Hit them hard with an Fiendsmith's Agnumday equipped to Fiendsmith's Desirae! 
- Outgrind, outfight your opponent and set up an unaffected towers in Fiendsmith's Rextremende!

While most of the deck are individually powerful boardbreakers, this deck makes use of the Fiendsmith engine in order to have a recurring monster engine. Here is the short combo:

Fiendsmith's Sanct or Archfiend Eccentrick one-card combos:

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67570995 
  • D/D/D Wave High King Caesar combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67571184 

These combos are weaker than having a non-pendulum Light Fiend monster as a starter. You lose out on the ablility to have Lacrima the Crimson Tears + Fiendsmith's Requiem , which at baseline is a free monster and at ceiling can send Fiendsmith in Paradise (sending Fiendsmith's Desirae) for another interruption.

Lacrima the Crimson Tears one-card combos:

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67581722 
  • D/D/D Wave High King Caesar combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67581536

Lacrima the Crimson Tears with Fiendsmith Engraver allows us to have an interrupt through Fiendsmith in Paradise sending Fiendsmith's Desirae. This makes Lacrima the Crimson Tears hard to handtrap because they would need to negate both the on field effect and the GY effect (after Fiendsmith's Requiem is made). 

Fiendsmith's Sequence Fusion Summon (by shuffling back from GY):

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae: Most common, provides negates
  • Fiendsmith's Rextremende: Unaffected monster, useful when we wish to use boardwipes without losing our own monsters. Can also be summoned to recycle Runick Fusion monsters to the Extra Deck. 
  • The Duke of Demise: Used to recycle D/D/D Wave High King Caesar, Necroquip Princess, Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis, Chaos Angel back into the Extra Deck     
  • The Duke of Demise: Additional Normal Summon resummons Magical Musketeer Starfire, linking The Duke of Demise with Fiendsmith's Sequence for Fiendsmith's Agnumday to revive another lv4 LIGHT//FIEND to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight again with the lv4 and Magical Musketeer Starfire.  

Boardbreaking
- Destroy all of your opponent's monster negates
- Setup a situation to use Evilswarm Exciton Knight to destroy the field of Spell/Traps and Defensive monsters
- Evilswarm Exciton Knight is important - we are unlikely to have a battle phase to clear negated monsters with on our first turn. (by Domain Format rules)

Due to a desire to play a high density of Boardbreakers, we have scrapped the bottom of the barrel. Some of our boardbreakers will be more costly and less effective than others. Many of them negate instead of straight up destroying, and many of them will be negated rather than resolve. This means that our opponent's monsters may stay on the field and be able to annoy us the next turn which is why we want to use Evilswarm Exciton Knight to clear them. (This is especially important because in Domain only the 4th player gets a battle phase on their first turn, so 3/4 of the time we don't have a battle phase)

This deck is setup to specifically deal with monster-heavy boards, and will not do well against decks that setup negation in the Spell/Trap Zone. The primary goal is to deal with your opponent's endboards all at once thorugh Evilswarm Exciton Knight, which can be used multiple times if needed. 

Evilswarm Exciton Knight is extremely important because it is a boardwipe to all 3 opponent's fields. In addition, as a LIGHT//FIEND it can start the Fiendsmith's Requiem combo, and as an XYZ monster it can be used to summon Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder in case the fieldwipe failed. Keep in mind that Evilswarm Exciton Knight has no Once-Per-Turn and can be recycled into the Extra Deck using Fiendsmith Engraver.    

After clearing the boardstate, we will wish to lean on the Fiendsmith cards to keep us in the game. This is due to our Boardbreakers all being one-time use - after breaking the board once our hand will be exhasted.

A note on lack of Spell/Trap Removal: 
The most common set cards in Domain Format are boardwipes like Torrential Tribute , Needle Ceiling , and Book of Eclipse. While these cards can stop us from setting up Evilswarm Exciton Knight if they resolve, they also just do the job of Evilswarm Exciton Knight, so this deck's stretegy does not mind them too much. Outside of that, other common Spell/Traps are advantage generating s/t and Floodgates, neither of which this deck minds. Evilswarm Exciton Knight can destroy the Advantage generating S/T, and this deck plays so low to the ground that Floodgates hardly harm it. The most worrysome set card is negation. We will simply just need to play through the negation. 
By disregarding Spell/Trap Removal, we more increase our chance of having a hand that can deal with 3 monster boards - a tough ask by itself. 

Other Considerations:

Spell Speed Boardbreakers: Vesper Girsu , Flash of the Forbidden Spell , Xyz Import , That Wacky Alchemy! , Share the Pain , Dark Core , Parallel Twister , Tri-Brigade Roar , Red Arrows , Corridor of Agony , Forbidden Scripture , Hidden Fangs of Revenge , Metaltronus , Double Snare , Realm Eulogy , Super Polymerization , Original Bamboo Sword , Chaos End , Brain Control , Spell Card "Soul Exchange" (+ M7 or Duke  to add back Engraver )
Good Boardbreakers (subset of above): Xyz Import , Metaltronus , Realm Eulogy , Super Polymerization , Mystic Box 
Conditional, but powerful: Flash of the Forbidden Spell , Tri-Brigade Roar , That Wacky Alchemy! , Original Bamboo Sword , Chaos End 

Spells/Traps: Runick cards, Fiendsmith's Sanct , Torrential Tribute , Kyoutou Waterfront , Terraforming , Pot of Desires , Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole , Constellar Belt / Darkuriboh 

Monsters: Lava Golem , The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode , Archfiend Eccentrick , Constellar Ptolemy M7 (recycles Zeus) , Steelswarm Roach , Aerial Eater + Diabolica the Draconique General , Unchained Soul Lord of Yama + Unchained Soul of Sharvara , Sky Striker Ace - Roze (+ Sky Striker Alternative - Lemnis Gate), Combined Maneuver - Engage Zero! , Knightmare monsters , Arahime the Manifested Mikanko (slow) , Fairy Tail - Snow 

Removed from deck: 

Monsters: Magical Musketeer Caspar , Magical Musketeer Wild , Steelswarm Roach 
Spell/Trap: Magical Musket - Last Stand , Vesper Girsu , Flash of the Forbidden Spell , Xyz Import , Realm Eulogy , Super Polymerization , Mystic Box 

Other Variants:

Trap Heavy: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/fiendsmith-runick-paleo-558811 
LiveTwins: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/fiendsmith-live-twins-601324 
Trap Rageki: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/silver-fang-raigeki-573667 

Recap

Important Cards: Evilswarm Exciton Knight , Fiendsmith's Requiem , Lacrima the Crimson Tears 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Destroy them and watch them flounder.

Built to Unbuild, Shaped to Unshape.

Once upon a midnight dreary, while I pondered, weak and weary,

Over many a quaint and curious volume of forgotten lore—

    While I nodded, nearly napping, suddenly there came a tapping,

As of some one gently rapping, rapping at my chamber door.

“’Tis some visitor,” I muttered, “tapping at my chamber door—

            Only this and nothing more.”

 

    Ah, distinctly I remember it was in the bleak December;

And each separate dying ember wrought its ghost upon the floor.

    Eagerly I wished the morrow;—vainly I had sought to borrow

    From my books surcease of sorrow—sorrow for the lost Lenore—

For the rare and radiant maiden whom the angels name Lenore—

            Nameless here for evermore.

 

    And the silken, sad, uncertain rustling of each purple curtain

Thrilled me—filled me with fantastic terrors never felt before;

    So that now, to still the beating of my heart, I stood repeating

    “’Tis some visitor entreating entrance at my chamber door—

Some late visitor entreating entrance at my chamber door;—

            This it is and nothing more.”

 

    Presently my soul grew stronger; hesitating then no longer,

“Sir,” said I, “or Madam, truly your forgiveness I implore;

    But the fact is I was napping, and so gently you came rapping,

    And so faintly you came tapping, tapping at my chamber door,

That I scarce was sure I heard you”—here I opened wide the door;—

            Darkness there and nothing more.

 

    Deep into that darkness peering, long I stood there wondering, fearing,

Doubting, dreaming dreams no mortal ever dared to dream before;

    But the silence was unbroken, and the stillness gave no token,

    And the only word there spoken was the whispered word, “Lenore?”

This I whispered, and an echo murmured back the word, “Lenore!”—

            Merely this and nothing more.

 

    Back into the chamber turning, all my soul within me burning,

Soon again I heard a tapping somewhat louder than before.

    “Surely,” said I, “surely that is something at my window lattice;

      Let me see, then, what thereat is, and this mystery explore—

Let my heart be still a moment and this mystery explore;—

            ’Tis the wind and nothing more!”

 

    Open here I flung the shutter, when, with many a flirt and flutter,

In there stepped a stately Raven of the saintly days of yore;

    Not the least obeisance made he; not a minute stopped or stayed he;

    But, with mien of lord or lady, perched above my chamber door—

Perched upon a bust of Pallas just above my chamber door—

            Perched, and sat, and nothing more.

 

Then this ebony bird beguiling my sad fancy into smiling,

By the grave and stern decorum of the countenance it wore,

“Though thy crest be shorn and shaven, thou,” I said, “art sure no craven,

Ghastly grim and ancient Raven wandering from the Nightly shore—

Tell me what thy lordly name is on the Night’s Plutonian shore!”

            Quoth the Raven “Nevermore.”

 

    Much I marvelled this ungainly fowl to hear discourse so plainly,

Though its answer little meaning—little relevancy bore;

    For we cannot help agreeing that no living human being

    Ever yet was blessed with seeing bird above his chamber door—

Bird or beast upon the sculptured bust above his chamber door,

            With such name as “Nevermore.”

 

    But the Raven, sitting lonely on the placid bust, spoke only

That one word, as if his soul in that one word he did outpour.

    Nothing farther then he uttered—not a feather then he fluttered—

    Till I scarcely more than muttered “Other friends have flown before—

On the morrow he will leave me, as my Hopes have flown before.”

            Then the bird said “Nevermore.”

 

    Startled at the stillness broken by reply so aptly spoken,

“Doubtless,” said I, “what it utters is its only stock and store

    Caught from some unhappy master whom unmerciful Disaster

    Followed fast and followed faster till his songs one burden bore—

Till the dirges of his Hope that melancholy burden bore

            Of ‘Never—nevermore’.”

 

    But the Raven still beguiling all my fancy into smiling,

Straight I wheeled a cushioned seat in front of bird, and bust and door;

    Then, upon the velvet sinking, I betook myself to linking

    Fancy unto fancy, thinking what this ominous bird of yore—

What this grim, ungainly, ghastly, gaunt, and ominous bird of yore

            Meant in croaking “Nevermore.”

 

    This I sat engaged in guessing, but no syllable expressing

To the fowl whose fiery eyes now burned into my bosom’s core;

    This and more I sat divining, with my head at ease reclining

    On the cushion’s velvet lining that the lamp-light gloated o’er,

But whose velvet-violet lining with the lamp-light gloating o’er,

            She shall press, ah, nevermore!

 

    Then, methought, the air grew denser, perfumed from an unseen censer

Swung by Seraphim whose foot-falls tinkled on the tufted floor.

    “Wretch,” I cried, “thy God hath lent thee—by these angels he hath sent thee

    Respite—respite and nepenthe from thy memories of Lenore;

Quaff, oh quaff this kind nepenthe and forget this lost Lenore!”

            Quoth the Raven “Nevermore.”

 

    “Prophet!” said I, “thing of evil!—prophet still, if bird or devil!—

Whether Tempter sent, or whether tempest tossed thee here ashore,

    Desolate yet all undaunted, on this desert land enchanted—

    On this home by Horror haunted—tell me truly, I implore—

Is there—is there balm in Gilead?—tell me—tell me, I implore!”

            Quoth the Raven “Nevermore.”

 

    “Prophet!” said I, “thing of evil!—prophet still, if bird or devil!

By that Heaven that bends above us—by that God we both adore—

    Tell this soul with sorrow laden if, within the distant Aidenn,

    It shall clasp a sainted maiden whom the angels name Lenore—

Clasp a rare and radiant maiden whom the angels name Lenore.”

            Quoth the Raven “Nevermore.”

 

    “Be that word our sign of parting, bird or fiend!” I shrieked, upstarting—

“Get thee back into the tempest and the Night’s Plutonian shore!

    Leave no black plume as a token of that lie thy soul hath spoken!

    Leave my loneliness unbroken!—quit the bust above my door!

Take thy beak from out my heart, and take thy form from off my door!”

            Quoth the Raven “Nevermore.”

 

    And the Raven, never flitting, still is sitting, still is sitting

On the pallid bust of Pallas just above my chamber door;

    And his eyes have all the seeming of a demon’s that is dreaming,

    And the lamp-light o’er him streaming throws his shadow on the floor;

And my soul from out that shadow that lies floating on the floor

            Shall be lifted—nevermore!

$50 Budget Super Quant Decklist (Pre-DUAD). Feel free to adjust ratios based on availability and budget.

Main Deck choices:

10 Super Quant monsters + 2 field spells. 6 normal summons for a 40 card deck.

Vingolf's Blessing: New common from ALIN. It can send White Layer to GY on activation to search Alphan from deck or GY. If sent to GY via Dangers, field spell discard, or Grampulse's S/T destruction, it can revive an Alphan from GY.

Foolish Burial has more flexibility for other Super Quant effects, while Vingolf's has two effects in one card and can be run at 3 copies. Either works well with Super Quant!

Emergency Teleport + Minimalian: Additional special summons of Blue Layer to search a needed Quant card.

Danger engine: XYZ materials and cycling cards to GY.

Speedroid engine: Great opener engine to summon Gossip Shadow for hand trap protection, or XYZ Armor Torpedo for a draw + Armor engine access, without using your normal summon.

Full Armor engine: Discard fodder + rank up used XYZs into Dark Lancer. Armored Shark can be substitued for the equip spell. If Magnus is equipped with a Super Quant XYZ by Full-Armored XYZ's effect, then he will gain the attack boost and destruction protection!

Called By The Grave, Crossout Designator, and 10 hand traps: Counter/interrupt the opponent. Use whichever hand traps you like/can afford. Ghost Ogre can be summoned from deck on the opponent's turn via Emergency Teleport for interaction.

Extra Deck choices:

Gossip Shadow: Hand trap/monster effect negate. Can rank up into Armor engine after detaching it's materials.

Promethean Princess + Sunlight Wolf: Princess can revive Red Layer for GY recursion/discard fodder to make Magnaliger + Sunlight Wolf for removing Promethean Princess' fire summon lock + additional recursion of Red Layer/Ash Blossom from GY. This engine helps push for Magnus if you are able to make 2 other mechs and have another monster on board + Red Layer in GY that hasn't used the on-summon effect this turn.

Worldsea Dragon Zealantis: Board wipe + retrigger your Super Quant on summon effects (Blue revived by Red is the usual use case)

Lyrilusc Nightingale + Zeus: Use with Alphan's level modulation to threaten a board wipe or stall for one turn.

Avramax: Alternative boss monster if you can't reach Magnus. This can be replaced with the Super Quant Link 3 or I:P Masquerena

deck_excerpt: We banishing even more fish with this one
deck_description:
My build for ghoti with the new stuff from ALIN, it is still a 2 card combo and those 2 combo pieces need to work with each other. You still get some awkward hands.

Some of my thoguhts on how I like to play the deck:

Aspischool

The art is derpy but it is realy cool as an starter for the deck, being able to unclog a hand that would be really hard to play with in the past: cases when psiics was stuck in your hand and there would be little way to get them into the field. The banish upon leaving the field on the additional summon can cut on resources but is a net positive when it just triggers a ghoti,make sure to load the GY first.

When banished from GY to summon Psiics from banish, Aspischool can be chain link 2 in the new chain and now your Psiics can't be ashed.

Adamancipator Crystal - Dragite

You may get lucky and hit it with Dragite effect and then non target bounce, and if you add nibiru to the deck you will probably get a bounce or two after deck tining a little. In the GY, you can start recycling some of your synchro ghoti like Askaan that only banish on summon.

Eria the Water Channeler

Personally, I like this card though 'll admint you can play any other card and it would be fine, is a nearly universal searcher for the whole deck if the other monster is a lvl 2. You can get those pesky Ghoti lvl 6 into the graveyard and add a Tidal or the other Ghoti lvl 6.

Lifeless Leaffish

The old starter of the deck, you can probably run 3 and cut the charmer. In hand where both Aspischool and Leaffish are available, I'll say, normal the Aspischool and summon the Leaffish with the effect, you get both effects. Is at 2 since i really dont want to see more than one of these in hand. Remeber to recycle your spents synchro fishes!

Tidal, Dragon Ruler of Waterfalls

Use the effect in hand to send Mirror Mage to the GY and also load the GY. The summon effect can guarantee that we always have the Ghoti in rotation as you banish them to summon Tidal everyturn, Aspischool will trigger with this and you also get a free body. 

Moray of Avarice

With Aspischool it felt really good, before, you would need one Ghoti lvl 2 or a loaded GY if used on the big ones, with Aspischool, you get the 2 cards and the body back.

Toxic Boxfish

Can start the loop or restart it if your Psiics is stuck in the graveyard or disrupt your opponent in the turn with the summon and banish effect. It is not unrealistic to trigger both in the turn it is summoned and with Keaf, you can recicle the negate if need be.

Number 37: Hope Woven Dragon Spider Shark

I'm sure there a better rank 4 water that is not banned, but the intention is to crash and have White Aura whale come back after it has been dealt with, enfatically, White Reincarnation should be on the field so you get the Raigeki effect and double attack.

Graydle Dragon

A neat thing to summon with mirror mage to pop 4 (!) and if destroyed, we get to recyle maybe White Aura Whale once again.

Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen

Just here to make something with Tidal that I never get to play, maybe just put Trishull, Navy Dragon Mech, Vermilion Dragon Mech or Crocodragon.

Mermail King - Neptabyss

Before Neptabyss the last link in the deck was the link 4 Marincess Bubble Reef, with Neptabyss we get target protection, wich was devastating in the past if one of our tuners gets imperm'ed. We can protect our key pieces on the board like Dragite, Chengying or the tuners. Any effect that is a must resolve should be done under Neptabyss, it doesnt always work but it does surprisinglyoften.

idk i wanted to create something new! as usual
This is the most optimal build I could think of for gate guardian.

Check out my Facebook:

https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=61567425458021

 

Check out my Instagram:

https://www.instagram.com/raigekiyugioh

Pile I made a few weeks ago, that shocked me by its quality. 

The deck can play through mulcharmies while setting up few points of interaction.

It flows strangely nicely, namely the odion package can search Scorpion which acts as fodder for the Regenesis monsters, while also leaving 2 bodies either for fiendsmith combo (either desirae or Wave King High Ceasar+Lacrima trap line) and still setting up 2 apophis traps.

Bystials are the only part of the deck that you can cut down on, they work nicely with the Regenesis monsters but you will be bricking on regained as if it was stuck to your hand by sheer magic.

Going first it builds incredible boards, which also have great recursion due to the regenesis, bystial and fiendsmith packages which allow you to win in simplified board states, outgrinding your opponent. For the same reason it wins while making half board very often.

These were the pros, now the cons.

The apophis package is very bricky going second (shocker, being on ten traps and an temple of the kings can make your hands unplayable, who knew).

It requires a lot of good decision making into mulcharmies-the lines are incredibly convoluted and at times asinine.

And lastly, it struggles against droll. You can eat most handtraps easily, but droll can make or break games often. Also, its on a low non-engine count, and while it has enough gas to play into boards very often, if your opponent is on mermail (where your bystials are useless) and you didnt draw non-engine, its game over.

Also, the side is very bad, please give me suggestions.

To summarize, incredibly fun deck to pilot that can stand against the meta!

deck_excerpt: I stared at WAKE CUP! Mocha for too long and got this
deck_description:
So WAKE CUP! Mocha was revealed in DUAD, and as a Flip Monster that can flip a face-down monster on the field face-up while also Special Summoning itself from hand, it is a great Flip Monster extender for making Subterror Behemoth Fiendess. However, after some pretty quick deliberation, it is not good in Prediction Princess because we would have to be playing a large number of low Level Flip Monsters while also hard drawing Mocha in order to even Summon it by its effect. And then you would need enough Flip Monsters to open a good number of them in your hand to even use the effect of Behemoth Fiendess. The Decks that I feel could make the best use of Mocha are Krawler and a Subterror Deck playing a large number of Behemoths. Prediction Princess is not one of these Decks. But I did see that it is an Aqua monster, and it just so happens that a certain Level 9 Fusion Monster needs Aqua monsters as material: Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart. So after some Deck-building attempts and testing, I still concluded that WAKE CUP! Mocha is just not playable in Prediction Princess, even Tearlaments Prediction Princess because of you having to hard draw it so often. But in the process, I was able to refine my previous Tearlaments Prediction Princess Deck quite a bit. It still is nothing that you should actually be playing, but it is a better representation of what a Tearlaments Prediction Princess Deck should look like. 

To refresh everyone’s memory, Tearlaments has 1 Level 9 monster in Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart which is a Level 9 DARK Fiend Fusion Monster that requires Tearlaments Reinoheart and 2 Aqua monsters as material. It cannot be used as Fusion Material, and if it is Special Summoned or if an Aqua monster is sent to your GY by a card effect while it’s on the field, you can target a card your opponent controls and shuffle it into the Deck. Then, if it is sent to the GY by a card effect, you can Special Summon it, and then you must send a Tearlaments card from your Deck to the GY. Kaleido-Heart is one of the best Level 9 monsters you could be playing in Prediction Princess simply because of how synergistic its effects are with various cards within the Deck. Mereologic Aggregator detaches its materials for effect, not cost, so when you are attaching Herald of the Arc Light from your GY and detaching Kaleido-Heart, Kaleido can just bring himself back which gives you that additional material on field to go into either S:P Little Knight or I:P Masquerena instead of being forced to Link Aggregator off into Gravity Controller. Furthermore, Kaleido-Heart’s effect to shuffle a card on field back into the Deck activates on Special Summon, not Fusion Summon, so Summoning him off of Summoner of Illusions will trigger his effect. Even bringing him back from GY with Nine-Lives Cat will do the same, not to mention that if he is used for another Aggregator, he will bring himself back again. Also, sending any Tearlament card from Deck to GY when he revives himself can give you a options such as sending Tearlaments Scream to search for either any Tearlament Trap or even sending a Reinoheart from Deck to GY to set-up a Fusion Summon play involving Subterror Behemoth Phospheroglacier on your opponent’s turn to make another Kaleido-Heart, which is what I am focusing on in this new version of the Deck.

Full combo is any way to dump Rainbow Bridge of Salvation into the GY and World Legacy Monstrosity. This is quite the unreliable combo to open, but I just want to reiterate that I am doing this whole thing of testing Level 9s with Prediction Princess just to test the potential options as well as to identify noticeable synergies between these cards. Specifically, this new Tearlaments Prediction Princess list is to refine and give a better interpretation of what such a Deck would look like, at least more optimally. Let’s say that you opened Foolish Burial Goods as your way to send Bridge to GY. Activate Goods to send Rainbow Bridge of Salvation from Deck to GY. Banish Bridge from GY to add a Crystal Beast Emerald Tortoise and a Primeval Planet Perlereino from Deck to hand. Activate Perlereino to add Tearlaments Reinoheart from Deck to hand. Normal Reinoheart and activate his effect on Normal Summon to send any Tearlaments name from Deck to GY, let’s say that you sent Tearlaments Scheiren. Scheiren activates in GY to Fusion Summon Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart by placing herself from GY, Reinoheart from field, and Emerald Tortoise from hand on the bottom of your Deck. Activate Monstrosity targeting Kaleido-Heart to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Kaleido-Heart into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers to add Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Aggregator activates its other effect, targeting Herald in GY, and detaching Kaleido-Heart to attach Herald from GY. Kaleido-Heart triggers after being sent to GY to Special Summon himself back and sending Reinoheart from Deck to GY. Link Aggregator and Kaleido-Heart into I:P Masquerena. Herald triggers again in GY to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers to Special Summon herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei’s effect to flip Bibliomuse face-up, which then triggers her Flip Effect to search for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck. Activate the second Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down using Bibliomuse. Proceed to the End Phase, and Tarotrei Special Summons Deus-X Krawler from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from your GY to activate its effect and chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith is flipped face-up and then Underworld Ritual Special Summons Bibliomuse from Deck face-down. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Subterror Behemoth Phospheroglacier from Deck face-down and then chain its other effect to flip both Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up. On a new chain, Bibliomuse uses her Flip Effect to add another Tarotrei and Underworld Ritual from your Deck to your hand. Now, you have Deus-X negating all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field, Bibliomuse searched follow-up and is providing targeting and destruction protection to your Ritual Monsters, I:P Masquerena can Link Summon Borrelguard Dragon using itself and 2 other monsters (not Deus-X), Borrelguard can then Quick Effect flip Phospheroglacier face-up which triggers its Flip Effect to send either Scheiren or Merrli from Deck to GY, their effect would then trigger to place itself, Reinoheart, and Phospheroglacier on the bottom of the Deck to Fusion Summon another Kaleido-Heart to spin a card, and Perlereino can also pop a card when your Tearlaments are returned to Deck.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 1 Subterror Behemoth Phospheroglacier. We are only using it for its Flip Effect which sends a card from your Deck to the GY like a budget Beatrice. Sadly, it is not as good as Beatrice as its effect to send any card from Deck to GY is stuck on a Flip Effect, but it does have some utility as a Flip Monster in Prediction Princess, like being able to dump a Tearlament to Fusion Summon Kaleido-Heart on our opponent’s turn in this Deck. We are just playing 5 Tearlament monsters: 3 Tearlaments Reinoheart, 1 Tearlaments Scheiren, and 1 Tearlaments Merrli. Reinoheart sends a Tearlaments monster from Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon, and aside from being a named material on Kaleido-Heart, that is pretty much all that we are using him for. As for Scheiren and Merrli, we are just using them for their GY effect which is if they are sent to the GY by a card effect, you can Fusion Summon a monster by placing materials from your hand, field, and/or GY on the bottom of your Deck including itself. I’m not excluding Havnis on purpose, but we do not need that many names in this Deck. Even 1 name could work, but we need to ensure that we can actually send one off of Reinoheart. Drawing it would essentially kill the combo. 1 Crystal Beast Emerald Tortoise to search off of Rainbow Bridge of Salvation and it is an Aqua to make Kaleido-Heart. Finally, 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, and 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos. Drawing Foolish Burial Goods and World Legacy Monstrosity is really unruly, so this Deck intends to go second and hopefully draw into combo through the Mulcharmies which is, again, not great but it does work better than praying to draw combo going first. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 2 Primeval Planet Perlereino which adds a Tearlaments monster or a Visas Starfrost from Deck on activation. While it is on field, all Fusion Monsters and Tearlaments monsters you control gain 500 ATK. And if a Tearlaments monster(s) you control or in your GY is returned to the Deck or Extra Deck, you can target and destroy a card on field. We don’t need to maximize on this card because we are intending to use Rainbow Bridge of Salvation as the main way to Perlereino to get Reinoheart. Opening Perlereino by itself means that you don’t have a second Aqua monster unless you open Purulia, Phospheroglacier, Tortoise, or a Tearlament name in your starting hand, so you can’t make Kaleido-Heart off of Reinoheart through this. Also, unlike my previous list, we are not playing Tearlaments Perlergia because I don’t know what happened to me when I was making the previous list to make myself forget about the existence of Rainbow Bridge of Salvation, which literally is the card that gets you to Kaleido-Heart by itself compared to Perlergia which requires you to open both it and Reinoheart. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Foolish Burial Goods. 1 Triple Tactics Talent. 3 Forbidden Droplet not only as a going second card, but as a way to get a Rainbow Bridge of Salvation out of your hand and into the GY. Speaking of, 2 Rainbow Bridge of Salvation which you can banish from GY to search for a Crystal Beast and a Field Spell from Deck. 

Extra Deck: 2 Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer and 1 K9 - EX “Werewolf” as removal and large attackers that can be used to go into Zeus. 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Nine-Lives Cat which is a Rank 9 that prevents your opponent from targeting other monsters you control that were Special Summoned from the GY with card effects. This effect really doesn’t do anything unless you somehow make it turn 1 and keep it around to prevent your opponent from Imperming your Deus-X Krawler on their turn or something. But, it can also detach a material and target either a Level 9 in your GY or a monster in your opponent’s GY and Special Summon that monster. Again, this can bring back a Kaleido-Heart to use its effect to spin a card on the field, but it can be also used to get something from your opponent’s GY as well. 1 Borrelguard Dragon which is a LINK-4 that requires 3+ Effect Monsters as material and cannot be destroyed by card effects. We are mainly using it for its Quick Effect which targets a monster on field and changes it to face-up Defense Position whereas this effect’s activation cannot be responded to by your opponent’s cards or effects.You may not have seen me use or really talk about this card much, but it is good, specifically as a Link Summon off of I:P Masquerena on your opponent’s turn (since that’s when you will usually have enough material to do so) in order to have a way to flip up a Flip Monster that was Special Summoned by Tarotreith from Deck at the moment that you need to do so. In that case, as described in the combo above, you would chain Tarotreith’s effect to flip any number of face-down monsters you control face-up to her Flip Effect that Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. That ensures that Deus-X and Bibliomuse are face-up on field as soon as possible for protection and to negate the activation of your opponent’s monster effects on their field. Borrelguard can then be Link Summoned via I:P using herself, Tarotreith, and probably either Tarotrei or Bibliomuse since they’ve done their job in setting up your Flip Monsters, especially Deus-X. Now, for the Flip Monsters whose Flip Effects are most useful when timed correctly (i.e. Summoner of Illusions Special Summoning a Fusion Monster with an effect that activates on Special Summon, Pot of the Forbidden’s Raigeki effect, Greed Jar in general, etc.), Borrelguard will be able to facilitate them via its effect at the right moment. Issue is that you usually do not have the material to make it Turn 1, so I:P going into it on your opponent’s turn is the most optimal way to get it out. Unless you are playing Symphonic Prediction Princess that is, which is bad, but it does do it (I will post this Deck someday). Finally, 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena.

Side Deck: 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Fire Princess FTK ft. Home Stadium + Spell Absorption + Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Hello there! Here, a trio of Fire Princess + Home Stadium + Spell Absorption can burn the opponent to death. If you wonder how, let's get into action.

 

 

Gameplan

1) With Monk or Pendulum/Double Summon, have Princess at your side. "Seventh Tachyon" might help you in that regard with Number 105, just like how Number 104 would fetch Monk/Library.

2) If you have played "Land Flipping" to place "Chicken Game" at opposing side, XYZ Summon Diamond with 2 x Level 4 monsters except Princess as materials. Use Diamond to destroy Chicken at opposing side.

3) Activate 2 x Spell Absorption. These will let you gain LP and you can start blasting with Princess. To make it endless loop, play first Home Stadium and then play the other one. For each spell you have played in general, you will gain 2 x 500 = 1000 LP in total from 2 x Absorption, which is enough to gather first Home Stadium from GY/BZ by paying 1000 LP.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Wonder Wand" + "Spellbook of Secrets" + "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR + 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Trade-In" can be collected by purchasing "Origin of the Galaxy" deck. 90 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Summoner Monk" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Chicken Game" can be found within "The Most Dangerous Race of the Cosmos!" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Performapal Monkeyboard" can be found within "The Bizarre Playing Board" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Land Flipping" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 UR!

- "Diamond Dire Wolf" can be found within "Forest Friends" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 105: Battlin' Boxer Star Cestus" can be found within "Blazing Warriors" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Argostars - Home Stadium" can be found within "Wrath of the Tyrants" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 480 SR and 270 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Thanks to the introduction of the rest of the Fiendsmith cards into Masterduel, Magical Musketeer is propelled into full power competition!
deck_description:
With the release of Lacrima the Crimson Tears and Agnumday in Masterduel, Fiendsmith is now full power! This means that strategies that make full use of Fiendsmith can now flourish, including Magical Musketeer!
 
The ridiculously powerful link-1s of both Magical Musketeer (Magical Musketeer Max) and Fiendsmith (Fiendsmith Requiem) give the strategy a lot of resilience through interruption and the ability to generate a lot of bodies for link summoning. If one archetype gets handtrapped (for example, when you summon Max), you can easily pivot to the other archetype (link away Max for Requiem) since both link-1s require only a light fiend monster! Handtraps are easily brushed aside in this strategy, with only the most powerful handtraps like Mulcharmy Fuwalos and Dimension Shifter able to fully stop the turn. Due to the sheer amount of link material, Magical Fiendsmith also can also tap into Unchained, giving you access to resource recursion and extra interruption through Unchained Soul of Yama and Unchained Soul of Rage. 
 
If your opening hand has both Magical Musket and Fiendsmith, this deck ends on a whopping 5-6 layered interruptions! On top of that, this deck sports room for 21 staples, with 17 of them being handtraps! If you're looking for a deck to hardcounter combo heavy decks like White Forest while being able to withstand a ton of handtraps/interruption from midrange decks like ---, you've chosen the correct deck to pilot!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Magical Musketeer Fiendsmith is actually technically made out of 3 fiend archetypes, with the main two mentioned in the name and the third being Unchained. The other half of the deck is composed of staple cards, mostly consisting of handtraps. 
 
FIENDSMITH is the main "engine" that keeps this deck running, and is a recurring engine that recycles light fiends that keeps the grindgame of this strategy going. Since it is the main strategy, the Fiendsmith cards are maxxed out for extra consistency. The Fiendsmith spells are also maxxed out since they have synergy with the Magical Musket monsters. It is composed of x3 Engraver, x3 Lacrima the Crimson Tears, x3 Tract, x3 Sanct, x1 Lurrie and x1 Paradise. 
 
The MAGICAL MUSKETEER package in this deck is minimal, and it's used primarily as a way to generate extra link material, bait interruption, and to provide more fusion material for the summon of Fiendsmith Desirae. It is composed of x3 Starfire and x1 Calamity in the maindeck. There is x1 Max in the Extra Deck. Despite the low count of Magical Musket monsters, these cards are recyclable from the graveyard due to the Fiendsmith cards.
 
The UNCHAINED cards are a mini package in this deck that raises the power ceiling of the endboard. There are only two cards in the maindeck - x1 Sharvara and x1 Escape of the Unchained. Given you have enough link material, you can end on both Unchained Soul of Rage and Fiendsmith Desirae, complete with a set Escape of the Unchained and an Unchained Yama in the graveyard. If fully set up, these cards adds an extra 4 interruptions to your endboard (Rage's link away, S:P's double banish, and Escape's pop!)
 
STAPLES form nearly half of the cards in this strategy! A whopping 17 handtraps are used. The usual Maxx "C" package is used, with the addition of Psy-Frame Gamma and Driver. 
 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Fiendsmith Magical Musketeer is adaptable - it can create a board with multi-layered interactions, with up to 6 interruptions + handtraps in hand! Or it can play low to the ground - for example if your opponent activates Maxx "C" or a Mulcharmy, - you can just give your opponent a singular draw while you set up your entire gameplan! 
 
This deck functions as a grindy midrange control deck that specializes in destroying combo-centric strategies. The duelist simplifies the gamestate by drowning their opponent in handtraps, then using the combined resource generating power of Fiendsmith, Magical Muskets and Unchained. Overtime, the duelist should overpower their opponent with a gigantic Fiendsmith Desirae and his other fiendish homies. 
 
Here is the best possible board available with Magical Musketeer Fiendsmith: 
 
Magical Musketeer Starfire + Fiendsmith Engraver + Either Fiendsmith Tract/Sanct = Fiendsmith Desirae (omni-negate on field), Fiendsmith in Paradise in GY (targeted send to GY if it sends Desirae from Extra Deck), Unchained Soul of Rage (links away opponent's monster into S:P Little Knight x2 banish, also it recycles fiends from GY), Escape of the Unchained (targeted pop), Unchained Soul of Yama in GY (summons fiend from GY), Lacrima of the Crimson Tears (generates follow-up for next turn)
  1. Normal summon Magical Musketeer Starfire. 
  2. Discard Fiendsmith Engraver to search for Fiendsmith Tract. 
  3. Activate Fiendsmith Tract in the S/T zone behind Starfire to search for Fabled Lurrie, then discard Lurrie. 
  4. CL1 Lurrie's mandatory effect to summon from GY, CL2 Starfire's effect to summon from deck Magical Musketeer Calamity. 
  5. Link summon Magical Musketeer Max using Starfire. 
  6. Link summon Fiendsmith Requiem using Lurrie. 
  7. Activate Fiendsmith Sanct in the S/T zone behind Calamity to summon a Fiendsmith Token. 
  8. Activate Calamity's trigger effect to summon from the GY Starfire. 
  9. Activate Fiendsmith Requiem's effect to summon from deck Lacrima of the Crimson Tears. 
  10. Lacrima's on-summon effect sends to the GY Fiendsmith In Paradise. 
  11. Link summon Unchained Soul Lord of Yama using Magical Musketeer Max + Fiendsmith Token. 
  12. Yama's on-summon effect searches for Unchained Soul of Sharvara from deck. 
  13. Summon from the GY Engraver by shuffling back into Extra Deck Magical Musketeer Max.
  14. Link summon Fiendsmith's Sequence using Lacrima + Engraver. 
  15. Activate Sequence's effect to fusion summon Fiendsmith Desirae by shuffling back Engraver + Calamity + Lurrie. 
  16. Activate Sharvara's effect in-hand to destroy Sequence. 
  17. Link summon Unchained Soul of Rage using Sharvara + Yama. 
  18. Sharvara's trigger effect when sent to the GY sets from deck Escape of the Unchained. 
  19. Activate Sequence's effect in the GY to equip itself to Fiendsmith Desirae. 
With this endboard, you have Desirae's omni-negate, the targeted-send of Fiendsmith in Paradise (send Desirae from Extra), Soul of Rage's link -> S:P Little Knight's double banish, Escape of the Unchained's targeted pop, and the follow-up for next turn with Requiem/Lacrima and Rage/Yama! On top of that, this deck contains a ton of handtraps as well! All opponents are generally hard pressed when facing this strategy because of the barrage of handtraps followed by the overwhelming grindgame of Fiendsmiths and Magical Musketeers! 
 
HELP! I'VE BEEN  MAXX C'D! 
 
In this scenario, you normal summon your light fiend, then you link summon into Fiendsmith Requiem. That way, you'd give your opponent only one draw! During your opponent's turn, you tribute Requiem to summon Lacrima from deck, and she sends to the GY Fiendsmith in Paradise which is one interruption. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Remember, this deck's main condition is to simplify your opponent's gamestate with handtraps while outgrinding your opponent of resources. Try not to give your opponent extra draws with Maxx "C" or the Mulcharmies! 
  • Magical Musketeer Max is an excellent way to bait interruption going second! If your opponent doesn't stop it, you get a lot of free advantage!
  • If you are struck with a Mulcharmy Fuwalos, simply just normal summon a light fiend and summon Fiendsmith Requiem, giving your opponent extra card to draw. During your opponent's turn, tribute Requiem to summon Lacrima from deck, sending to GY Paradise for an interruption! 
  • The natural counter to handtrap-centric decks like Fiendsmith Magical Musketeer are trap decks. Trap decks generally don't care about handtraps too much, and since there is no main or side-decked backrow hate they tend to flourish. Beware of decks like Labrynth! 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I've always liked midrange decks that can support a ton of handtraps or staples. It allows for the best Yugioh to happen, where both duelists have a back-and-forth trading resources, cards and monsters on the battlefield. Fiendsmith Magical Musketeer allows for that! You can go either first or second, and actually play proper games vs. almost any deck this format can throw at you! Also, something is so unfathomably cool and unfair when you use a link-1 of 1 archetype to pivot into another link-1 monster of a second archetype! The unique identity of Fiendsmith Magical Musketeer as the premier "link-1" deck and the fun characteristics of its gameplay make this deck one of my favourites to ever pilot. 
 
GLHF Duelists!
ryzeal mitsu

Explode!!!

The pen is mightier when it draws removal.
A Budget deck that utilizes Folgo, Justice Fur Hire to draw 3 every turn, drawing removal. Unfortunly the Extra Deck is not well utilized. 

Deckmaster: Rex, Freight Fur Hire 
Domain Restriction: EARTH // DINOSAUR // FUR HIRE 
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into 3 broad categories:

  • Card Draw
  • Removal
  • Monster Flood

Primary Packages: Fur Hire   

Recommended Guide: (from Courtesy)
https://youtu.be/JliwK7BcaKk

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Rex, Freight Fur Hire 
- Small and Cute
- Combo Starter by adding Rookie Fur Hire 
- Revives Folgo, Justice Fur Hire 

Rex, Freight Fur Hire alongside any monster can get us a combo into Folgo, Justice Fur Hire and 2 other Fur Hires. This strategy uses Rookie Fur Hire in order to summon Beat, Bladesman Fur Hire , summoning Donner, Dagger Fur Hire. 

Rex, Freight Fur Hire has a GY effect to summon a monster Fur Hire from GY or add back a Fur Hire spell/trap. This allows us to recur Folgo, Justice Fur Hire from the graveyard or add back Mayhem Fur Hire. 

Card Draw
- Folgo, Justice Fur Hire draws 3
- Rafale, Champion Fur Hire escavates cards
- Draw more Card Draw
- Draw Removal
- Draw Monsters
- Drown them in card advantage

If you don't have what you need, just use card draw to find it! This strategy primraly uses Folgo, Justice Fur Hire in order to draw cards, but we also supplement it with Pot cards since we don't care about our Extra Deck. 
In order to trigger the Card Draw from Folgo, Justice Fur Hire we need removal.  

If we have enough card draw, we will eventually have more cards than our opponents. This can be done if we Folgo, Justice Fur Hire draw 3 as much as possible, which allows us to use 1-for-1 card trades without feeling bad about it. 

Removal
- Take care of Threats
- Trigger Folgo, Justice Fur Hire 
- Trade cards for threats

Any form of destruction removal, spell/trap or monster, will trigger Folgo, Justice Fur Hire to draw. This draw is beneficial by giving us more removal! Our constant sources of removal are Unending Nightmare and Bottomless Shifting Sand. 

By having so much card draw, we can feel better about 1-for-1 removal. Will your opponent have more threats than we will have removal in hand?

 Monster Flood
- Fur Hire summons Fur Hire monsters from hand
- Free Summons to combo with Rex, Freight Fur Hire and Rookie Fur Hire 

Any monster with Rex, Freight Fur Hire that searches Rookie Fur Hire allows us to combo into Folgo, Justice Fur Hire with 2 Fur Hire monsters. This can be done with any monster that special summons itself from hand like Dinowrestler Pankratops and Alpha, the Master of Beasts. This can also be done with any Fur Hire monster in hand by using Beat, Bladesman Fur Hire to summon that monster Fur Hire. We have over 20 monsters that falls into these catagories, which allows us to have over 90% consistancy on the first turn. (However, this also means we draw these monsters instead of removal)

Because of our Card Draw, having monsters that can summon from hand are great, so we don't waste cards!

Other Options

Monsters: Shield of the Millennium Dynasty , K9 - 17 Izuna 

Spells/Traps: Reasoning

Outside Domain: Runick  
Other Deckmasters: Rafale, Champion Fur Hire 

Recap:

Important Cards: Folgo, Justice Fur Hire , Mayhem Fur Hire 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Outpace them through superior card advantage.

Best Budget Upgrades: Gordian Slicer , Kashtira Fenrir , Forbidden Droplet , Sengenjin Wakes from a Millennium 

Ink, instinct, and initiative.

deck_excerpt: Brotherhood of the Tri-Brigade ft. Zeroboros
deck_description:
Get Eagle on the field asap and start spamming your Fire Fist effects without coughing up your formation spells. Alternatively, use Fraktall or Kerass to send monsters to your GY and banish to link summon. When your opponent's field gets too oppressive, link summon Topologic Zeroboros, special summon a Fire Fist monster where it points to, and have fun resummoning every turn with an ATK boost for every banished card.

I've been workshopping this deck since 2022 and got it to a point where I feel like it's reached its max potential. I'm currently gold in Master Duel with this deck and slowly working my way up.

deck_excerpt: For those wishing to play an archetype that features the cards within that archetype. You will probably lose a lot though.
deck_description: This deck will probably be better played in a casual setting. Feel free to add or remove the cards you feel are useless. (Timaeus, Dark Magician, Dark Magic Mirror Force, etc.) I just get tired of seeing an archetype be played with only a select few of the cards within that archetype. That is mostly due to the state of "Modern Yu-Gi-Oh." If you aren't running staple cards or another archetype that makes the deck better (At this moment: Fiendsmith/Primite in Master Duel), then you are just going to lose. I'd rather lose while playing 70% of an archetype than win with only two cards from it.

deck_name: Budget Fire King (Post ALIN, NO IMPULSE)
deck_description: Budget build for Pure Fire Kings post Alliance Insight (no Impulse bc my ahh is poor </3). Lots of Fiendsmith hate, anti-Maliss cards, and favorable Mitsu matchup. S:P >>> TY-PHON because you're either creating a lot of simplified gamestates or are in a grind game with FS. Veilers in side instead of Imperms since (1) they can be used for Almiraj in a pinch and do not conflict with Nib/Bystials and (2) Impulse isn't in the deck. Sunlight Wolf >>> Duelittle because you usually only need the Kirin add-back once for when you opened it in the starting hand and Duelittle lines are more awkward.

Playing style[edit]

The "Gem-Knight" archetype is based around Fusion Summoning, accomplished with the use the archetype's many Fusion Summon-Spells/Traps and a wide array of recycling effects.

The original "Gem-Knight" cards focused on a Beatdown/Toolbox strategy, where a variety of "Gem-Knight" Fusions could be made with Gem-Knights in hand. More recent support has instead enabled an FTK strategy, using the effects of "Lady Lapis Lazuli" and "Master Diamond" to burn the opponent.

Just Offers a bunch of different ways to get what you want and mill your opponents extra deck, focusing on getting alba zoa as he is really the powerhouse, white relic is just there if you get in a attack pinch that daogamatikacism cannot fix. Offers a rushed way to get some branded monsters on the field if all else fails. Really doesnt like going against decks that dont care about their extra deck and are mainly regular monster focused like dark magician decks, floowandereeze and Kashtira. Other than that tearlemants can just move from graveyard to field too easily to keep up with. Things to watch out for are really just cards that bansih instead of going to the graveyard(masked hero dark law, dimension shifter) as well as Destiny Hero Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer as his ATK lowering ability is not negated by Alba Zoa. Another Key note is that you kind of have to not brick to get off a succesful round 1 by milling or setting up a borad that cant be touched by the extra deck. That being said I've had alot of success going second as the different avanues can bait out abilities and reach a decent borad. If anybody has any tweaks or tips they are welcome. Obviously its not a top tier deck and can get countered somewhat easliy but I enjoy the cards and not being able to be affected by the extra deck is satisfying (especially if they dont read). 

Accomplishments:

Diamond 1, multiple in game events can be cleared with tiny tweaking

deck_excerpt: This is a completely legal (As of May 22nd 2025) decklist for the TCG combining Atlateans, Frogs, and an Armored XYZ package.
deck_description:
This deck is able to get a strong board with layers and is a lot of fun to play. If you are looking for an Atlantean deck to play without the degrenerate handrips and barrier statue lock then you came to the right list! 

Your main goal is to get Coelacanth (Level 7 fish) out and summon 2 level 3's and 2 level 4's (Only works if Coel is the only monster in the main monster zone; you can have coral/Nept in the extra monster zone and be fine). Then, Xyz summon Virtue, search for "Virtue stream" activate Virtue's effect to add a Fish, Sea serpent, or aqua and search for either Toad package or more Atlantean extenders/ Harpooner if you have the materials for dragite. Then, overlay into Fortress, search for Reincarnation and full-armor trap (If you have either in hand try to get fortress to only 1 mat to detach so lancer combo is possible during your oppenents turn.) It should be noted that IF YOU CAN try to get "Neptabyss The Royal Mermail" on field before detaching for cost for either virtue or Fortress to activate his effect to search for Abyss-sting to then reborn an Atlantean or Mermail monster depending on what you need for your end board!

or if you don't want to go into lancer package: Synchro Summon into Cora dragon, if you have Princess on field/ in hand with your normal summon you can; Normal summon princess, activate her effect as cost to send dragoon to GY, search for Deepsea minstrel or Shadow Squad (With dragoons mandatory search effect and depending on your situation and hand) and with Princess's effect add Poseidra to hand , then synchro in prima dona and try to get a level 3 tuner to go into chen or gymir depending on turn and board/ what your oppenent is playing.

Those are some baseline combo's you can do but I heavily recommend trying out different strategies. editting the deck to your playstyle, and experimenting with the many different lines this deck can follow depending on your opponents deck and whatever interruptions you encounter.

Also, if they were cheaper I would have added in some Mulcharmies or Impulse's.

deck_excerpt: Take the time machine back to 2007!
deck_description:
This is a rework of the 2007 "Starter Deck Jaden Yuki". The strangest thing about this deck is the complete lack of Jaden's signature fusion monsters. Even stranger is that many of the HERO fusion cards had been released by this point. I'm guessing that their idea was to just provide a base to add on to whatever HERO cards you may have collected at that point.

Using only cards that were included in the starter deck, I cut a handful of cards that are dead draws, and improved ratios for more important cards. All the HERO cards remained at 1x as they were included to maintain the spirit of the deck. I know Avian is useless in this deck - use him as discard fodder.

Gemini Elf  was bumped up to 3x - it's a fantastic normal monster if you're reliving the early 2000s formats. Rush Recklessly and Smashing Ground were both bumped up to 2x. Rush Recklessly is an underrated Quick-Play that can easily catch your opponent off guard once they think all your battle traps are taken care of. Trap Hole was bumped up to 2x as it's a no-brainer for easy removal. The rest of the trap ratios remained the same as I actually really like the lineup and it maintains the spirit of the character.

That's about all for today! Try it out against starter deck Syrus Truesdale. I'll tackle that one next.

deck_excerpt: Standard Puppet FTK with a few tweaks
deck_description:
Here's a standard Gimmick Puppet FTK wih a few changes, i.e.:

Main deck Ogre and Nib for hand trap / removal to help with a clear board for FTKs, and extra draw power to fuel the FTK

I've seen a lot of decks still using Terror baby, i quite like to play one incase fiendish knight gets belled, or crowed etc. it's also nice to be able to utilise the extra normal under some circumstances. we're also playing extra copies of dreary doll and bisque doll (supporting the trade-ins / allure, and bricking respectively)

I personally like to run 3 Trade-Ins and 2 Allure but 1 Allure is good for consistency or if you end up banishing too much engine.

Since the banlist, having mansion is practically necessary for FTKs though if you survive a bystial (or go second) you can also bring that back with fiendish knight or CXyz Machinix for bonus damage.

I Personaly like to play more handtraps for targets for the Puppet Shark / general interuption (hence why theres a load (also ofr options) in the side).

Finally, as an extra note: the extra deck can be filled with spare copies of the puppets for grind games, i just wanted to show the minimun necessary for the FTK / short games.

 

WHAT TO DO WHEN YOU GET HANDTRAPPED:

Do NOT concede, attempt to make a copy of CXyz Machinix, place either one of the traps (depending on which one you are running), and attempt to sit on a wall of handtraps / big monsters for a turn. (it's also worth considering running a copy of pot of avarice if you're getting stuck at the end of long grind games without any lvl8s, or a Hope Harbinger).

deck_excerpt: Tired of losing the coinflip? Time to play a "coin-flip proof" deck - Sky Striker Tenpai!
deck_description:
While climbing up Masterduel ladder, I once had a 10-in-a-row coinflip loss... NOW IT'S TIME FOR PAYBACK!!!

Blind-second Sky Striker Tenpai doesn't care about the coinflip, since it blinds second and everyone wants to go first in this meta! The current Masterduel meta is a slogfest of unbreakable FTK boards, every deck has a bazillion handtraps/extenders, and everything is a combo "pile" deck of Fiendsmith, Azamina, Millenium, Snake-Eyes, Blue-Eyes, Yubel and White Forest. BOOOORING! While your opponent spends 10+ minutes building their board, get yourself a snack, obtain some water, wash some dishes, clean up your room, then come back to OBLITERATE their board with your power spells, Sky Striker arsenal, and their lifepoints with Tenpai Dragons!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!
